‚úÖ NOTES (Concepts: SQL JOINs & How They Work)
üîπ What the video covers
It explains core types of table joins in SQL: INNER JOIN, LEFT JOIN, RIGHT JOIN, and FULL JOIN ‚Äî how they combine rows from two (or more) tables based on matching column(s). 
It uses visual diagrams to help understand which rows appear depending on join type, especially useful when tables have overlapping or non-matching rows. 

üîπ Why joins are needed
Real-world databases split related data across multiple tables.
To gather combined information (e.g. user + orders, student + classes, products + suppliers), you must join tables on appropriate keys.
Joins let you relate tables logically and fetch combined results in a single query.

üîπ Common types of JOINS explained
Join Type	What it returns / When to use
INNER JOIN	Rows that have matching values in both tables ‚Äî only overlapping data. 
LEFT JOIN (or LEFT OUTER JOIN)	All rows from the left table, plus matching rows from the right. For left rows without match ‚Äî right side becomes NULL. 
RIGHT JOIN (or RIGHT OUTER JOIN)	All rows from the right table + matching from left. Left side NULL where no match. (Note: some SQL dialects ‚Äî e.g. certain versions ‚Äî may or may not support RIGHT JOIN.) 
FULL JOIN (FULL OUTER JOIN)	All rows from both tables; matched where possible; non-matches from either side appear with NULL for missing fields. 

üîπ How JOIN works (mechanics / matching)
You specify a join condition, usually something like tableA.key = tableB.key.
SQL engine compares rows between tables, finds matching pairs, then builds output rows according to join type (only matches, or all + matches, etc.).
Column naming/aliasing helps avoid ambiguity when multiple tables have columns with same name.

üîπ When to use which join
Use INNER JOIN when you only want records present in both tables.
Use LEFT JOIN when you want all records from primary/left table, whether or not there‚Äôs matching data in the other table (e.g. all users, with or without orders).
Use RIGHT JOIN if you want all rows from right table ‚Äî but often you can swap table positions + use LEFT JOIN if RIGHT JOIN isn't supported.
Use FULL JOIN when you want everything ‚Äî records present in any table ‚Äî and want to preserve unmatched rows too.

üîπ Best Practices & Things to Watch
Always specify join conditions clearly (on which columns to join) ‚Äî to avoid unintended ‚Äúcartesian products‚Äù (every row combined with every row).
Use table aliases (e.g. u, o) to make queries readable and disambiguate columns.
Be mindful of NULL values: with outer joins, unmatched side yields NULLs ‚Äî handle them appropriately (e.g. with COALESCE, conditional logic).
Choose minimal required columns to fetch (avoid SELECT * unnecessarily) ‚Äî better performance and clarity.

üìù PART 2 ‚Äî EXAMPLES (SQL JOIN Queries & Use Cases)
Let's assume two tables:
Customers
customer_id | name      | city  
--------------------------------  
1           | Alice     | Mumbai  
2           | Bob       | Delhi  
3           | Carol     | Pune  
4           | Dave      | Mumbai  

Orders
order_id | customer_id | order_date  | amount  
---------------------------------------------  
101      | 1           | 2025-11-20  | 2500  
102      | 3           | 2025-11-22  | 1500  
103      | 1           | 2025-11-25  | 500  
104      | 5           | 2025-11-26  | 3000   -- note: customer_id = 5 does not exist in Customers  

‚úÖ Example A ‚Äî INNER JOIN (only matching customers with orders)
SELECT c.customer_id, c.name, o.order_id, o.amount
FROM Customers c
INNER JOIN Orders o
  ON c.customer_id = o.customer_id;

Result rows:
Alice (customer_id 1) ‚Äî orders 101, 103
Carol (customer_id 3) ‚Äî order 102
Because only those customers have matching orders in Orders. Customer Bob and Dave (no orders) are excluded. Order 104 with customer_id 5 excluded (no matching customer).

‚úÖ Example B ‚Äî LEFT JOIN (all customers + their orders if any)
SELECT c.customer_id, c.name, o.order_id, o.amount
FROM Customers c
LEFT JOIN Orders o
  ON c.customer_id = o.customer_id;

Result rows:
Alice ‚Äî 101, 103
Bob ‚Äî NULL (no orders)
Carol ‚Äî 102
Dave ‚Äî NULL (no orders)
This shows all customers, and orders only where present.

‚úÖ Example C ‚Äî RIGHT JOIN (all orders + matching customers)
If your SQL supports RIGHT JOIN:
SELECT c.customer_id, c.name, o.order_id, o.amount
FROM Customers c
RIGHT JOIN Orders o
ON c.customer_id = o.customer_id;

Result rows:
Alice ‚Äî 101, 103
Carol ‚Äî 102
NULL ‚Äî 104 (order with customer_id 5, no matching customer)
This shows all orders, even those with no valid customer.
(If RIGHT JOIN not supported ‚Äî you can swap tables and use LEFT JOIN similarly.)

‚úÖ Example D ‚Äî FULL JOIN (all customers + all orders, matched where possible)
SELECT c.customer_id, c.name, o.order_id, o.amount
FROM Customers c
FULL OUTER JOIN Orders o
ON c.customer_id = o.customer_id;

Result rows:
Alice ‚Äî 101, 103
Carol ‚Äî 102
Bob ‚Äî NULL (no orders)
Dave ‚Äî NULL (no orders)
NULL ‚Äî 104 (order with no valid customer)
This gives the most inclusive view ‚Äî everyone from both tables.

‚≠ê Summary ‚Äî Why JOINS Matter & Key Points
Joins help combine related data from multiple tables based on relationships (keys).
Choosing correct join type is important depending on whether you want only matches, or all rows including non-matches.
Outer joins (LEFT/RIGHT/FULL) can produce NULLs ‚Äî plan logic accordingly.

Proper join conditions & column aliases help avoid mistakes and make queries readable.
